Filesystem tracepoints provide visibility into VFS and filesystem-specific operations: (1) VFS-level tracepoints: tracepoint:vfs:vfs_read, vfs_write, vfs_open, vfs_fsync. These capture all filesystem operations regardless of the underlying filesystem type. (2) Filesystem-specific: ext4:ext4_sync_file, ext4:ext4_da_write_begin; xfs:xfs_file_read, xfs_file_write; btrfs:btrfs_get_extent. (3) Block layer: block:block_io_start, block:block_io_done, block:block_rq_issue, block:block_rq_complete — trace I/O from filesystem to disk. (4) Analysis script:
```bash
# Monitor slow VFS operations (> 1ms)
bpftrace -e '
kprobe:vfs_read { @start[tid] = nsecs; @file[tid] = arg0; }
kretprobe:vfs_read /@start[tid]/ {
    $dur = nsecs - @start[tid];
    if ($dur > 1000000) {
        printf("Slow read: %s took %d us\n", comm, $dur/1000);
        @[kstack(5)] = count();
    }
    delete(@start[tid]); delete(@file[tid]);
}
'
```
(5) Identify slow paths: The stack trace from slow operations reveals whether the delay is in: (a) Page cache lookup (find_get_page — cache miss); (b) Block layer (submit_bio — I/O submission); (c) Filesystem journaling (jbd2 — transaction commit); (d) Lock contention (inode_lock — concurrent access). (6) ftrace approach: echo 'hist:keys=common_pid:vals=common_timestamp.usecs' > events/vfs/vfs_read/trigger builds a latency histogram for all read operations. cat events/vfs/vfs_read/hist shows the distribution.

