`irq_default_primary_handler()` is a minimal hardirq handler that simply returns `IRQ_WAKE_THREAD`. It is used as the hardirq handler when `request_threaded_irq()` is called with a NULL hardirq handler and `IRQF_ONESHOT`. Its implementation is trivial:
```c
static irqreturn_t irq_default_primary_handler(int irq, void *dev_id)
{
    return IRQ_WAKE_THREAD;
}
```
This handler exists because `request_threaded_irq()` requires a non-NULL hardirq handler (the IRQ core needs something to run in hardirq context to acknowledge the interrupt and decide whether to wake the thread). When all processing is done in the threaded handler (common for I2C/SPI devices), this default handler provides the minimal bridge. With `CONFIG_IRQ_FORCED_THREADING`, this handler replaces the original handler when forced threading is active.

