Linux kernel memory initialization during boot is a complex, multi-phase process that sets up the page tables, initializes the buddy allocator, and prepares all memory management subsystems.

**Phase 1: Very early boot (head_64.S, before C code):**
1. The CPU starts in real mode, transitions to protected mode, then to long mode (64-bit)
2. A minimal page table is set up in head_64.S:
   - Identity mapping for the kernel text (physical = virtual)
   - Kernel text mapped at __START_KERNEL_map
3. CR3 is loaded with early_top_pgt (early boot page table)
4. Jump to x86_64_start_kernel()

**Phase 2: Early C initialization:**
```c
void __init x86_64_start_kernel(char *real_mode_data)
{
    // Set up early console, traps, etc.
    // Call start_kernel()
}

void __init start_kernel(void)
{
    // Many subsystems initialized here
    setup_arch(&command_line);  // Architecture-specific setup
    mm_core_init();             // Memory management core init
    // ...
}
```

**Phase 3: setup_arch() — Architecture-specific memory setup:**
```c
void __init setup_arch(char **cmdline)
{
    // 1. Parse early parameters
    setup_memory_map();  // Build e820 memory map from BIOS/UEFI

    // 2. Initialize memblock allocator (boot-time allocator)
    // memblock is the allocator used before buddy is ready
    memblock_init();

    // 3. Set up direct mapping
    init_mem_mapping();
    // This creates the linear mapping: __va(phys) = phys + PAGE_OFFSET
    // Uses 2MB and 1GB huge pages for efficiency

    // 4. Set up zone boundaries
    zone_sizes_init();
    // Determines which PFNs belong to which zones
    // ZONE_DMA, ZONE_DMA32, ZONE_NORMAL

    // 5. Initialize sparsemem
    memory_present();   // Mark present memory sections
    sparse_init();      // Initialize sparsemem data structures
}
```

**Phase 4: init_mem_mapping() — Building the direct mapping:**
```c
void __init init_mem_mapping(void)
{
    // Walk the e820 memory map
    // For each RAM region:
    //   Create PUD-level (1GB) or PMD-level (2MB) entries
    //   where possible for efficiency
    unsigned long end = max_pfn << PAGE_SHIFT;

    // Map [0, end) physical → [PAGE_OFFSET, PAGE_OFFSET + end)
    kernel_physical_mapping_init(PAGE_OFFSET, end);
}
```

**Phase 5: Buddy allocator initialization:**
```c
void __init free_area_init(unsigned long *max_zone_pfn)
{
    // For each NUMA node:
    for_each_node(nid) {
        pg_data_t *pgdat = NODE_DATA(nid);

        // Initialize zones within the node
        for (zone = 0; zone < MAX_NR_ZONES; zone++) {
            struct zone *z = pgdat->node_zones + zone;

            // Set zone boundaries
            z->zone_start_pfn = zone_start_pfn;
            z->spanned_pages = zone_spanned_pages;

            // Initialize free_area lists
            for (order = 0; order < MAX_ORDER; order++)
                INIT_LIST_HEAD(&z->free_area[order].free_list);

            // Initialize watermarks
            z->watermark[WMARK_MIN] = ...
            z->watermark[WMARK_LOW] = ...
            z->watermark[WMARK_HIGH] = ...
        }
    }
}
```

**Phase 6: memblock to buddy handoff:**
```c
void __init memblock_free_all(void)
{
    // Transfer all free memory from memblock to buddy allocator
    // Walk memblock's free memory regions
    for_each_free_mem_range(i, nid, &start, &end) {
        // Add each page to the buddy allocator
        free_low_memory_core_early();
        // This calls __free_pages_bootmem() for each range
        // Pages go onto the appropriate free_area lists
    }
}
```

**Phase 7: Post-init:**
```c
// Initialize per-CPU pagesets
setup_per_cpu_pageset();

// Initialize kswapd threads
kswapd_init();

// Initialize slab caches
kmem_cache_init();
// Creates kmalloc caches, kmem_cache_cache, etc.

// Initialize vmalloc
vmalloc_init();
```

**Key boot-time allocators:**
1. **memblock**: Available from the earliest boot until buddy is ready. Allocates from the top of memory downward. Used for all early kernel allocations.
2. **Bootmem** (deprecated): An older boot-time allocator, replaced by memblock.
3. **Buddy allocator**: Becomes available after free_area_init() + memblock_free_all(). Takes over all memory allocation.

