CFS（完全公平调度器）使用红黑树跟踪每个任务的虚拟运行时间（vruntime），选择最小vruntime的任务执行。调度类：stop（最高）、deadline（EDF）、real-time（FIFO/RR）、CFS（NORMAL/BATCH）、idle（最低）。per-CPU运行队列，CPU间负载均衡。CONFIG_SCHED_SMT/MC感知拓扑。EEVDF作为CFS继任者正在开发中。 The kernel's completion API for async operation synchronization:
```c
#include <linux/completion.h>

struct async_work {
    struct completion done;
    int result;
    void *data;
};

/* Callback invoked by hardware/DMA interrupt */
static void async_callback(void *arg)
{
    struct async_work *work = arg;
    work->result = read_status_register();
    complete(&work->done);  /* Wake up waiter */
}

/* Synchronous wrapper around async operation */
int do_async_operation_sync(void *data)
{
    struct async_work work;
    init_completion(&work.done);
    work.data = data;

    submit_async_operation(data, async_callback, &work);

    /* Wait with timeout */
    if (!wait_for_completion_timeout(&work.done,
                                      msecs_to_jiffies(5000)))
        return -ETIMEDOUT;

    return work.result;
}
```

Per-CPU variables are a fundamental mechanism in the Linux kernel for avoiding locking overhead entirely by giving each CPU its own independent copy of a variable. Since each CPU only accesses its own copy, no synchronization is needed for local access.

Declaration and initialization (from <linux/percpu.h>):
```c
static DEFINE_PER_CPU(int, my_counter);
DEFINE_PER_CPU(unsigned long, irq_count);
struct my_data __percpu *pdata = alloc_percpu(struct my_data);
```

Access patterns:
```c
/* this_cpu_* operations — single instruction, no preempt disable needed */
this_cpu_inc(my_counter);
this_cpu_add(my_counter, 5);
this_cpu_read(my_counter);

/* get_cpu_var — disables preemption and returns pointer */
struct stats *s = &get_cpu_var(cpu_stats);
s->packets++;
put_cpu_var(cpu_stats);

/* Aggregating across all CPUs */
int total = 0;
for_each_possible_cpu(cpu)
    total += per_cpu(my_counter, cpu);
```

How they eliminate locking: Each CPU writes only to its own copy — no cache line sharing. this_cpu_* operations compile to single instructions atomic with respect to interrupts on the same CPU.

When preemption disable is needed: If accessing per-CPU data through a pointer (not this_cpu_* ops), you must disable preemption to prevent migration. this_cpu_* operations are safe even with preemption enabled.

Common use cases: Statistics counters, scheduler data (struct rq), softirq/tasklet state, RCU state, slab allocator per-CPU caches.

Limitations: Aggregation cost (iterating all CPUs), cross-CPU access requires care, memory overhead (N copies for N CPUs).

