Both provide release semantics, but they serve different purposes and have subtly different guarantees.

**smp_store_release**: A general-purpose release store.
```c
smp_store_release(&flag, 1);
/* Guarantees: All prior stores/loads are ordered before this store */
/* Paired with smp_load_acquire for communication */
```

**rcu_assign_pointer**: Specifically designed for publishing RCU-protected pointers.
```c
rcu_assign_pointer(gp, new_ptr);
/* Guarantees: All initialization of *new_ptr is ordered before
 * the pointer is published */
/* Paired with rcu_dereference for reading */
```

**Implementation difference**:
```c
/* On most architectures, they compile to the same instruction */
/* smp_store_release: STORE with release barrier */
/* rcu_assign_pointer: STORE with release barrier */

/* But rcu_assign_pointer has additional semantics: */
#define rcu_assign_pointer(p, v) ({ \
    uintptr_t _r_a_p__v = (uintptr_t)(v); \
    if (__builtin_constant_p(v) && (_r_a_p__v) == (uintptr_t)NULL) \
        WRITE_ONCE(p, (typeof(p))(_r_a_p__v)); \
    else \
        smp_store_release(&p, (typeof(p))(_r_a_p__v)); \
    _r_a_p__v; \
})
```

**The NULL optimization**: rcu_assign_pointer skips the barrier when assigning NULL, because NULL means 'no valid pointer' — there are no prior writes that need to be ordered.

**When to use each**: Use rcu_assign_pointer when publishing pointers read by rcu_dereference. Use smp_store_release for general flag-based synchronization. Using the wrong one may work on most architectures but is technically incorrect for the RCU guarantee.

