The MCS (Mellor-Crummey and Scott) lock is a scalable queue-based spinlock that minimizes cache coherence traffic by having each waiter spin on its own local memory.

**MCS lock principle**:
Instead of all waiters spinning on the same shared lock variable (which causes cache line bouncing), each waiter has its own node and spins on a flag in that node.

```c
struct mcs_spinlock {
    struct mcs_spinlock *next;   /* Next waiter in queue */
    int locked;                   /* 1 = still waiting, 0 = lock acquired */
};

/* MCS lock acquire */
void mcs_spin_lock(struct mcs_spinlock **lock, struct mcs_spinlock *node) {
    struct mcs_spinlock *prev;
    node->next = NULL;
    node->locked = 1;  /* Initialize as waiting */

    prev = xchg(lock, node);  /* Atomically set ourselves as tail */
    if (prev) {
        /* Queue was not empty — link ourselves and spin on OUR node */
        prev->next = node;
        while (READ_ONCE(node->locked))
            cpu_relax();  /* Spin on local memory — cache-friendly */
    }
    /* Lock acquired (either no predecessor or predecessor signaled us) */
}

/* MCS lock release */
void mcs_spin_unlock(struct mcs_spinlock **lock, struct mcs_spinlock *node) {
    if (!node->next) {
        /* Try to set lock to NULL — no waiters */
        if (cmpxchg(lock, node, NULL) == node)
            return;  /* No waiters — done */
        /* Someone just joined — wait for them to link */
        while (!READ_ONCE(node->next))
            cpu_relax();
    }
    /* Signal next waiter */
    WRITE_ONCE(node->next->locked, 0);
}
```

**Usage in the kernel**:

1. **OSQ (Optimistic Spin Queue)** in mutexes:
```c
/* kernel/locking/osq_lock.c */
struct optimistic_spin_queue {
    atomic_t tail;  /* Encoded CPU numbers */
};
/* Mutex waiters spin on OSQ before sleeping */
/* Each CPU has its own osq_node — MCS-like */
```

2. **qspinlock** MCS queue phase:
```c
/* When ticket/pending approaches fail, qspinlock uses MCS queue */
static struct mcs_spinlock mcs_nodes[4]; /* Per-CPU MCS nodes */
```

**Why MCS matters**:
- O(1) cache misses per lock/unlock (only predecessor/successor cache lines)
- O(n) total cache misses for n waiters (each spins locally)
- Compared to test-and-set: O(n^2) cache misses due to all spinning on same line

