pmd_alloc_one() allocates a single PMD page table page:

```c
static inline pmd_t *pmd_alloc_one(struct mm_struct *mm, unsigned long addr)
{
    struct page *page;
    gfp_t gfp = GFP_PGTABLE_USER;

    // Account to memory cgroup
    if (mm == &init_mm)
        gfp = GFP_PGTABLE_KERNEL;

    page = (struct page *)__get_free_page(gfp);
    if (!page)
        return NULL;

    // Initialize to zero
    clear_page(page_address(page));

    // Set up page table tracking
    if (!pgtable_pmd_page_ctor(page)) {
        free_pages((unsigned long)page_address(page), 0);
        return NULL;
    }
    return (pmd_t *)page_address(page);
}
```

The function allocates a zeroed page, initializes the split page table lock via pgtable_pmd_page_ctor(), and returns the page's address. If allocation fails at any step, previously allocated resources are cleaned up. The gfp flags differ for user vs kernel page tables — kernel tables don't need memcg accounting.

