The Linux kernel provides two spinlock types: `raw_spinlock_t` and `spinlock_t`. Understanding the difference is essential, especially for real-time kernel development.

**raw_spinlock_t**: A true spinlock on all kernel configurations, including PREEMPT_RT. It always busy-waits and disables preemption.

**spinlock_t**: On non-RT kernels, it is identical to raw_spinlock_t. On PREEMPT_RT kernels, spinlock_t is converted to a sleeping lock (rt_mutex) with priority inheritance.

```c
/* Non-RT kernel */
typedef struct raw_spinlock { arch_spinlock_t raw_lock; } raw_spinlock_t;
typedef raw_spinlock_t spinlock_t;  /* Same thing */

/* PREEMPT_RT kernel */
typedef struct raw_spinlock { arch_spinlock_t raw_lock; } raw_spinlock_t;
typedef struct { struct rt_mutex lock; } spinlock_t;  /* Sleeping lock! */
```

**When to use raw_spinlock**:
```c
/* Use raw_spinlock when you MUST have a true spinlock, even on RT: */
static DEFINE_RAW_SPINLOCK(irq_desc_lock);

/* In interrupt handlers that must not sleep */
raw_spin_lock_irqsave(&desc->lock, flags);
/* ... handle interrupt ... */
raw_spin_unlock_irqrestore(&desc->lock, flags);
```

**When to use spinlock**:
```c
/* Use regular spinlock for most kernel code */
static DEFINE_SPINLOCK(my_lock);

spin_lock(&my_lock);   /* Spinlock on non-RT, sleeping on RT */
/* ... */
spin_unlock(&my_lock);
```

**Key differences**:

| Property | raw_spinlock | spinlock (RT kernel) |
|----------|-------------|---------------------|
| Wait behavior | Always spins | Sleeps (rt_mutex) |
| Preemption | Always disabled | May be preemptible |
| Interrupt safe | Yes (with irqsave) | Depends on context |
| Priority inheritance | No | Yes |

**Rules**:
1. Use raw_spinlock only for code that absolutely must not sleep (e.g., interrupt descriptor management, scheduler internals)
2. Use spinlock for everything else — it provides better latency on RT kernels
3. raw_spinlock critical sections must be very short to avoid latency spikes
4. The scheduler itself uses raw_spinlock because the scheduler cannot sleep while making scheduling decisions

